The global Statement#If you need to modify a global variable from within a function, use the global statement. Including a line such as global eggs at the top of a function tells Python, “In this function, eggs refers to the global variable, so don’t create a local variable with this name.
def spam(): global eggs eggs = &#39;spam&#39; eggs = &#39;global&#39; spam() print(eggs)Result:
spam&ldquo;Automate the Boring Stuff with Python by Al Swigart, Chapter 4 - Functions&rdquo;
